ate, consider conventions for note content, formatting, and lifecycle (e.g., archiving outdated notes).  \n3. **Tooling Integration**: Ensure that CI/CD pipelines, code review tools, and IDEs handle Git notes appropriately (some tools may not display notes by default).  \n4. **Merge Conflicts**: Notes can conflict if multiple users edit the same note; establish a process for resolving note conflicts (e.g., manual edits or automated tools).  \n5. **Performance Impact**: Large repositories with extensive notes may experience increased fetch/clone times; monitor repository size and consider periodic cleanup if needed.  \n6. **Alternative Solutions**: Evaluate if Git notes are sufficient long-term or if more robust documentation systems (e.g., wikis, dedicated docs) are needed for complex knowledge management.\n\n---\n\n**Recommendation**  \nDocument this decision in a team README or onboarding guide, including setup instructions and examples of note usage. Consider a trial period to validate the workflow before full adoption.",
